Hi friends =F0=9F=91=8B,
Happy Friday and welcome back to our 29th Weekly Dose of Optimism. Not goin=
g to lie, this was one of the harder newsletters to write all year. My mind=
 is 100% on the Super Bowl this weekend. But we fight on and publish.
Before diving in, we wanted to highlight our most recent episode of Anton T=
eaches Packy AI [ https://substack.com/redirect/223ea5e7-432f-437d-8d9e-dbe=
e6e80a771?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNp=
U ], in which Packy and Anton discuss Chroma=E2=80=99s (Anton=E2=80=99s com=
pany) launch of Stable Attribution [ https://substack.com/redirect/2ca86469=
-d394-4512-a44e-ce0f93ad4eba?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXX=
epKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ]. The tool let's anyone find the humans behind AI gen=
erated images.
Now, let=E2=80=99s get to it.
The Weekly Dose is brought to you by=E2=80=A6Wander [ https://substack.com/=
redirect/8b685de5-e2aa-4e70-965f-5c1d9e2f901a?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T=
7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ]
Wander [ https://substack.com/redirect/8b685de5-e2aa-4e70-965f-5c1d9e2f901a=
?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ] has b=
een one of our most popular sponsors ever=E2=80=A6and there=E2=80=99s good =
reason: the vacation homes are dope (seriously, check out the homes) and it=
=E2=80=99s Atlas vacation rental REIT presents a unique investment opportun=
ity.=20
Wander [ https://substack.com/redirect/8b685de5-e2aa-4e70-965f-5c1d9e2f901a=
?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ] is a =
network of smart vacation homes that come with inspiring views, modern work=
stations, restful beds, hotel-grade cleaning and 24/7 concierge service =E2=
=80=93=E2=80=93 combining the quality of a luxury hotel with the space and =
comfort of a vacation home, only better. Don=E2=80=99t take my word for it.=
 Use promo code notboring for $250 off your next trip. (offer expires Monda=
y 2/13 at 11:59pm). Explore now. [ https://substack.com/redirect/8b685de5-e=
2aa-4e70-965f-5c1d9e2f901a?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXep=
KbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ]
But that=E2=80=99s only part of the story. Wander recently launched Atlas [=
 https://substack.com/redirect/196017e3-5cf7-457d-8234-3fe3ac07b255?j=3DeyJ=
1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ] =E2=80=93=E2=
=80=93 a first-of-its-kind vacation rental REIT that gives you the chance t=
o own a piece of their magical portfolio of homes. With Atlas, accredited i=
nvestors have the opportunity to earn income and diversify their portfolio =
without the headache and hassle of buying a property, renting it out, or ma=
intaining it.
Plus, right now new Atlas investors may get the chance to invest in Wander=
=E2=80=99s next round of funding. You can learn more on their website:
(1) Can India industrialize? [ https://substack.com/redirect/b36e744c-b7fa-=
43b3-bc1d-6bbdba82180c?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqO=
sa8-6m8ExkRNpU ]
Noah Smith [ https://substack.com/redirect/49f99192-ba18-4d4c-b64e-e62a33ad=
c4b1?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ] f=
or Noahpinion
Why is India the most important development story on Earth? Two reasons. Fi=
rst of all, sheer size; as of this year, India is the world=E2=80=99s most =
populous country, overtaking a now-shrinking China. And its population dwar=
fs that of every development success story I=E2=80=99ve written about in th=
is series so far, combined. But India isn=E2=80=99t just incomprehensibly e=
normous; it=E2=80=99s also still quite poor. Despite its remarkable 250% gr=
owth over the past three decades, it=E2=80=99s still poorer than almost any=
 other country I=E2=80=99ve discussed so far.
Noah Smith capped off an amazing series on economic development with his an=
alysis of India, which he claims is the most important development story in=
 the world. Why is it so important?=20
India is home to more poor people than any other country in the world. If I=
ndia can develop, that changes the entire fabric of society. Or as Smith pu=
ts it: =E2=80=9CWhen Malaysia or the Dominican Republic reaches upper middl=
e income status, it=E2=80=99s a good thing and a useful success story; if I=
ndia did the same, it would shake the world.=E2=80=9D
Smith presents a balanced look at the progress India has made, the challeng=
es it faces, and the opportunities ahead. Broadly, India=E2=80=99s infrastr=
ucture has been improving=E2=80=A6
but it should be manufacturing and exporting more. Smith suggests three ind=
ustrial policies:
Keep improving infrastructure, and make a big push to improve public educat=
ion
=E2=80=9CExport discipline=E2=80=9D through limited-time export incentives
Encouraging FDI, especially in the electronics industry, through the use of=
 improved SEZs, targeted deregulations, and taking advantage of =E2=80=9Cfr=
iendshoring=E2=80=9D
Ultimately, Smith is =E2=80=9Coptimistic about India=E2=80=9D =E2=80=94 the=
 country has economic and psychological momentum on its side, could benefit=
 from friendshoring and the West=E2=80=99s souring attitude to formerly-lar=
gest-country China, and a growing recognition of how important it could bec=
ome. Chak de India.=20
(2) The Drug Is a =E2=80=98Miracle=E2=80=99 but These Families Can=E2=80=99=
t Get It [ https://substack.com/redirect/7e17a574-559d-4fde-8d92-fa8912d010=
98?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ]
Stephanie Nolen [ https://substack.com/redirect/56f7f744-cda0-4271-ab45-527=
32ae5adb9?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNp=
U ] and Rebecca Robbins [ https://substack.com/redirect/6d08af1b-b1e1-4fb7-=
8826-1cdf99ba92bb?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6=
m8ExkRNpU ] for The New York Times
Until Vertex=E2=80=99s drugs, patients had few options, mainly palliative t=
reatment to help them breathe a bit better, and if they could get one, a lu=
ng transplant. Vertex=E2=80=99s drugs addressed the underlying cause of the=
 illness, preventing patients=E2=80=99 lungs from clogging in sludgy mucus.
Trikafta is stunningly effective at helping patients breathe better [ https=
://substack.com/redirect/f309b59d-e648-4f7b-8727-2dbf9f3d6c5c?j=3DeyJ1IjoiO=
XAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ], keeping them out o=
f the hospital and extending their lives. Patients and doctors say that the=
 drug=E2=80=99s power becomes evident almost immediately.
On the surface, this story is pretty shitty. Another pharma company selling=
 a drug with 98% margins and restricting life-saving access from poor peopl=
e. This is all true. I hope that Vertex, governments, NGOs, etc. can figure=
 out a way to work together and make Trikafta available and basically free =
to anyone that needs it.
The other side of the coin here is that Vertex =E2=80=94 a company we menti=
oned in our piece on Atomic AI [ https://substack.com/redirect/40ec95a3-f50=
a-49f4-ac23-d67e2fd6cb59?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKb=
qOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ] =E2=80=94 developed a treatment that now all-but cures a=
 disease that, just five years ago, was considered a death sentence by your=
 mid-30s. One of my best friends in the world, Charlie, has cystic fibrosis=
 and struggled to find a treatment for most of his life. Here=E2=80=99s how=
 he described the impact of Trikafta:
Trikafta completely flipped my life. I went from three, hour-long sessions =
each day=E2=80=A6which still resulted in declining health, to taking two pi=
lls twice per day and leading an otherwise =E2=80=9Cnormal=E2=80=9D life.
Charlie is lucky in that he lives in the U.S. and has good insurance. For t=
hose outside of the U.S., especially in poorer countries, I am hopeful that=
 organizations and governments can work together to bring this treatment to=
 those that need it. It=E2=80=99s really one of those =E2=80=9CARE YOU FUCK=
ING KIDDING ME JUST GIVE THESE KIDS THE TREATMENT=E2=80=9D situations that =
with enough awareness should be resolved.
*In the U.S., if you=E2=80=99re looking to support under-insured folks get =
life saving treatments, I=E2=80=99d recommend taking a look at Healthwell [=
 https://substack.com/redirect/3de5e73c-19a3-4f1f-8d9b-a2dcb7f691b1?j=3DeyJ=
1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ], The Patient =
Advocate Fund [ https://substack.com/redirect/00d1de3d-0559-4056-b28b-66a21=
7018563?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU =
], and The Assistance Fund [ https://substack.com/redirect/ae5dbeda-efb1-47=
9a-ac22-c249331a9e29?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa=
8-6m8ExkRNpU ].
(3) =E2=80=9CFlorida Man=E2=80=9D Wins Seven Marathons on Seven Continents =
in Seven Days [ https://substack.com/redirect/f4dd8c96-8aca-4ac4-8aa1-9a92c=
3c82421?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU =
]
Brian Metzler [ https://substack.com/redirect/8bd60150-293e-4d58-8820-ba6f6=
582f5f9?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU =
] for Outside via @0xgaut [ https://substack.com/redirect/f8e1f24a-ea64-484=
b-9b3b-19cf306c82a2?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8=
-6m8ExkRNpU ]
David Kilgore just ran=E2=80=94and won=E2=80=94seven marathons in seven day=
s on seven continents. The 31-year-old American runner averaged about 2:56 =
per marathon, which means he ran 183.4 miles at 6:43 pace per mile.
Chalk this one up in the category of humans just pulling off wildly impress=
ive stuff. Seven Marathons. In seven Days. On seven Continents. Kilgore ran=
 183.4 miles in a week at an average pace that would be considered =E2=80=
=9Ca good mile time=E2=80=9D for your average adult male runner.
This isn=E2=80=99t the first time, or even the fastest, that someone=E2=80=
=99s completed the 7/7/7 =E2=80=94 =E2=80=9CAmerican Mike Wardian, who won =
the World Marathon Challenge in 2017 and 2019, still holds the record for t=
he fastest average time of 2:45:57=E2=80=9D =E2=80=94 but when Gaut sent th=
is over, we couldn=E2=80=99t help but feel inspired by what humans can do (=
and a little lazy).=20
(4) Concrete traps CO2 soaked from air in climate-friendly test [ https://s=
ubstack.com/redirect/22fe1739-a513-4255-9438-d3cfdbc9ffa9?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ=
3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ]
The joint effort between Heirloom and Canada's CarbonCure Technologies was =
the first time that carbon dioxide absorbed from the atmosphere using such =
Direct Air Capture (DAC) technology had been secured in concrete, where the=
 CO2 will stay put for centuries, several scientists said.
In a transition to net-zero emissions, two things need to happen. First, we=
 need to emit less CO2. That=E2=80=99s most important. Second, we need to c=
apture and remove CO2 that=E2=80=99s already been emitted. Easier said than=
 done, on both fronts.
We=E2=80=99ve covered DAC a bit at Not Boring and it=E2=80=99s the focus ar=
e of Frontier, the advance market commitment from Stripe, Meta, Alphabet, S=
hopify, and McKinsey to buy an initial $925M of permanent carbon removal.=20
A number of startups, some backed by Frontier, have taken similar approache=
s to capturing CO2 and storing it in different materials. The approach cove=
red in this article is notable largely because it=E2=80=99s the first time =
CO2 pulled from the air via DAC has been secured in concrete, and because h=
ow widely concrete is used and how carbon intensive it is.=20
The approach is a double-whammy: 1) concrete can store CO2 for centuries an=
d 2) mixing the CO2 into concrete cuts the need for cement, the part of con=
crete with the biggest carbon footprint. This first run was just =E2=80=9Ca=
 thimbleful of emissions abatement,=E2=80=9D and the technology needs to sc=
ale from kilograms to gigatons to make an real dent, but it=E2=80=99s a goo=
d proof point with huge potential.=20
(5) Go Birds =F0=9F=A6=85
We=E2=80=99re sorry, but we=E2=80=99re gonna have to be homers for a minute=
=2E It=E2=80=99s Super Bowl Week.
The Philadelphia Eagles don=E2=80=99t play many away games. They=E2=80=99re=
 on the road as much as any other team in the NFL, but wherever they=E2=80=
=99re playing, the Eagles fanbase dominates the stadium in such a way that =
it feels like home. We Philly fans are famous (or infamous) worldwide for o=
ur passion.
It=E2=80=99s tough to describe to someone not from the Philadelphia area wh=
at the Eagles mean to the city. We=E2=80=99re having an uncharacteristicall=
y great sports year across the board =E2=80=94 the Phillies made the World =
Series and the Sixers are #3 in the East =E2=80=94 but the Eagles are the t=
eam in Philly.=20
I=E2=80=99d imagine something like ~25% of the population would claim that =
the 2018 Super Bowl was the best day of their life=E2=80=A6and that that nu=
mber would rise to ~50% for single, children-less populations. For better o=
r worse, the mood of the city ebbs and flows with the success of the Eagles=
=2E
And the mood is pretty damn high right now. For good reason. This Eagles te=
am is lovable:
Dominant, but doubted all season long
Overlooked, but poised young quarterback in Jalen Hurts
Energetic coach that=E2=80=99s adopted his city=E2=80=99s blue collar and u=
nderdog persona
Lovable, veteran leaders in Jason Kelce and Brandon Graham
Roster constructed of high-flying superstars and unknown guys stepping up
This O-Line Christmas Album [ https://substack.com/redirect/cca4cfc7-abd4-4=
81e-9994-f7cc979e3f2b?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOs=
a8-6m8ExkRNpU ]
This list could go on and on, but we'll just leave you with some hype video=
s below that get the point across more effectively than I ever could.
If you want something to be a little extra optimistic about this weekend, w=
e invite all of you to be Eagles fans on Sunday. =20
Go Birds baby! =F0=9F=A6=85
